{
  "query": "What are the documented effects on wild bees of introducing agri-environment schemes on European farmland?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across Europe, replicated trials reported mixed effects of agri-environment schemes on wild bees: four trials documented enhanced diversity and/or abundance of foraging wild bees on scheme-managed land, including under Swiss Ecological Compensation Areas, a German organic arable option, Dutch botanical and meadow bird agreements (with very low bee species numbers), and the Scottish Rural Stewardship Scheme (including nest-searching queen bumblebees) [24]. Four other replicated trials found no enhancement of bee numbers or species under schemes, including Dutch meadow bird agreements in wet grassland, Spanish measures around a National Park and for steppe-living birds, and 6 m grass margin strips in England [24]. At wider landscape scales in the UK, two replicated trials found bumblebee populations were not enhanced on farmland with schemes\u2014one comparing Bombus terrestris colony reproductive success and another comparing spring queen numbers on farms with and without schemes [24]. Syntheses of invertebrate responses under European schemes reported variable outcomes: studies showed schemes maintained or had little/no effect on some invertebrates including bee colony growth, while others found increases in invertebrate abundance or richness; one UK study recorded local but not landscape-scale increases in bee numbers under scheme prescriptions [700].",
  "action_ids": [
    "24",
